ls, as they look for affordable, clean, and flexible sources of energy to f=
uel their every growing resource needs.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">First, Amazon =
has signed three new agreements to support the development of nuclear energ=
y projects, including Small Modular Reactors (SMRs), and announced its inve=
stment in SMR maker, X-Energy. Amazon is investing over $500 million to dev=
elop SMRs, partnering with Dominion Energy to explore building an SMR near =
an existing nuclear facility in Virginia, and collaborating with Energy Nor=
thwest to construct four advanced SMRs in Washington state. </p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">Not to be outdone, Google signed a groundbreaking agreement with Kai=
ros Power to purchase energy from a fleet of SMRs to power its AI data cent=
ers. The deal involves six to seven SMRs, with the first reactor expected t=
o be operational by 2030 and the rest coming online by 2035, providing a to=
tal of 500 megawatts of clean, continuous power.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">SMRs =
are hot. They are nuclear fission reactors that are significantly smaller a=
nd more compact than traditional nuclear power plants, and typically genera=
te up to 300 MWe of electricity. SMRs are designed to be factory-built, eas=
ily transported, and installed on-site in modules, offering greater flexibi=
lity and lower costs compared to large-scale nuclear plants. </p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Amazon and Google may prefer SMRs due to their scalability, reduc=
ed capital investment, smaller physical footprint, and enhanced safety feat=
ures, allowing for easier integration into their existing data center infra=
structure.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That said, both X-Energy and Kairos are pla=
nning to build advanced reactors &#8212; never before approved by the NRC &=
#8212; using advanced TRISO fuels. Amazon is not one to waste money (Google=
, maybe, but not Amazon!), so their involvement is both a sign that they be=
lieve there&#8217;s a path to approval and another set of muscles in the pu=
sh to get these incredibly safe, potentially cheap reactors approved. </p><=
